event: response.output_text.done
data: {"type":"response.output_text.done","content_index":0,"item_id":"msg_0089040ccfe40a250169e450fece2081909bdfd51350c665cf","logprobs":[],"output_index":1,"sequence_number":517,"text":"The smallest prime number greater than 100 is **101**.\n\n### Step-by-step explanation (why 101 is prime)\n1. **List candidates greater than 100**  \n   Numbers after 100: 101, 102, 103, ...  \n   We check **101** first.\n\n2. **Check divisibility by 2**  \n   - 101 is odd, so it’s **not divisible by 2**.\n\n3. **Check divisibility by 3**  \n   - Sum of digits of 101: \\(1+0+1=2\\)  \n   - Since 2 is not divisible by 3, **101 is not divisible by 3**.\n\n4. **Check divisibility by 5**  \n   - A number divisible by 5 must end in 0 or 5.  \n   - 101 ends in 1, so **not divisible by 5**.\n\n5. **Find what’s enough to test (use \\(\\sqrt{n}\\))**  \n   - If 101 were composite, it would have a factor ≤ \\(\\sqrt{101}\\).  \n   - \\(\\sqrt{101}\\approx 10.05\\).  \n   - So we only need to test primes ≤ 10.05, i.e. **2, 3, 5, 7**.\n\n6. **Check divisibility by 7**  \n   - \\(7 \\times 14 = 98\\)  \n   - \\(7 \\times 15 = 105\\)  \n   - 101 is between 98 and 105 and not equal to either, so **101 is not divisible by 7**.\n\n### Conclusion\nSince 101 is not divisible by **2, 3, 5, or 7** (and these are all primes up to \\(\\sqrt{101}\\)), **101 has no divisors other than 1 and itself**, so it is **prime**.\n\n✅ **Smallest prime greater than 100: 101**"}

